WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:16.120
I'm really excited to be here today to have this opportunity to talk with you and be invited

00:00:16.120 --> 00:00:18.600
to give a talk.

00:00:18.600 --> 00:00:22.480
And so first I want to say I get to be the one here to give a talk.

00:00:22.480 --> 00:00:28.000
But what I'm going to talk about today is the contributions of many people that make

00:00:28.000 --> 00:00:33.799
all of this work possible and drive the energy and enthusiasm of this project and so much

00:00:33.799 --> 00:00:34.799
of what we talk about.

00:00:34.799 --> 00:00:41.119
I mean, so just in this room, contributing to what I'm going to talk about today, we

00:00:41.119 --> 00:00:47.320
have Mine and Jenny and two of our staff here, Kerry Jordan and Francois Bicheno.

00:00:47.320 --> 00:00:51.360
We have Greg Wilson, the founder of Software Carpentry, Jason Williams, who served on the

00:00:51.360 --> 00:00:55.439
Executive Council of Software Carpentry, Kate Hurtwick, who's on the current Executive Council,

00:00:55.439 --> 00:00:58.560
and Martha Graham on the Data Carpentry Executive Council.

00:00:58.560 --> 00:01:05.160
So this is really a community effort, and so I want to attribute that and represent

00:01:05.160 --> 00:01:11.360
that in this talk because it's a part of that inclusive approach that we're trying to take.

00:01:11.360 --> 00:01:15.879
So I think we've seen throughout this meeting something that's really important is that

00:01:15.879 --> 00:01:22.000
we now have data and tools to advance progress and address questions in science and society.

00:01:22.000 --> 00:01:26.120
There's so much potential in what everybody's been talking about in the last couple of days

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:27.120
with the data.

00:01:27.120 --> 00:01:32.199
And then just, I mean, the revolution in the tools available in the art ecosystem has been

00:01:32.199 --> 00:01:34.440
amazing over the last couple of years.

00:01:34.440 --> 00:01:39.760
We're in a place where we weren't even a couple years ago.

00:01:39.760 --> 00:01:44.639
And we still talk a little bit, though, about the compute and the data.

00:01:44.639 --> 00:01:48.680
How do we bring compute to data or data to compute?

00:01:48.680 --> 00:01:55.959
But we need to talk about how we scale our impact, talking about bringing people to data.

00:01:55.959 --> 00:01:57.900
So you're in this room.

00:01:57.900 --> 00:01:59.879
You could be at any other talk.

00:01:59.879 --> 00:02:02.760
You could be doing anything else with your life.

00:02:02.760 --> 00:02:06.779
Why is this the most important thing to be talking about?

00:02:06.779 --> 00:02:10.279
Why is teaching people how to work with data?

00:02:10.279 --> 00:02:11.679
We have a lot of social challenges.

00:02:11.679 --> 00:02:14.119
Why is this one the most important?

00:02:14.119 --> 00:02:20.199
And so I want to point to this quote from Yashmi Milner, who's the founder of Data for

00:02:20.199 --> 00:02:22.160
Black Lives.

00:02:22.160 --> 00:02:27.919
And that data becomes a tool of profound social change or a weapon of political warfare depending

00:02:27.919 --> 00:02:30.440
on whose hands it is in.

00:02:30.440 --> 00:02:35.279
So we need to think about, as we have this data, that this data is power.

00:02:35.279 --> 00:02:41.119
And that we need to democratize these skills to give people the power of thinking about

00:02:41.119 --> 00:02:45.720
where they're headed, of how to interpret data, how to use data to answer the questions

00:02:45.720 --> 00:02:47.679
that are important for them.

00:02:47.679 --> 00:02:52.960
So this, to me, is one of the most important questions that we're facing right now as we

00:02:52.960 --> 00:02:59.440
look ahead to where we're going and seeing a data-driven world ahead of us, in fact,

00:02:59.440 --> 00:03:04.160
that we're in already.

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:08.720
So then if this is the most important question, getting more people to be able to work with

00:03:08.720 --> 00:03:13.919
data, how do we scale the number of people who can do this?

00:03:13.919 --> 00:03:16.559
So that's what we're trying to think about in the Carpentries.

00:03:16.559 --> 00:03:21.360
So the Carpentries is a nonprofit organization, and we're an open global community teaching

00:03:21.360 --> 00:03:25.399
researchers the skills to turn data into knowledge.

00:03:25.399 --> 00:03:31.199
And we do this through curriculum, open collaborative curriculum, an instructor training, teaching

00:03:31.199 --> 00:03:37.360
people how to teach, and community by building and fostering a community around these practices

00:03:37.360 --> 00:03:41.800
and about sharing knowledge.

00:03:41.800 --> 00:03:44.479
So I'm going to try an analog survey approach here.

00:03:44.479 --> 00:03:46.600
We'll see how it goes.

00:03:46.600 --> 00:03:53.520
So in reflecting on your own learning experiences, who in this room has been, and I'm going to

00:03:53.520 --> 00:03:57.919
tell you a way to answer this question, who in this room has been in a course or a workshop

00:03:57.919 --> 00:03:59.839
where they felt like they didn't belong?

00:03:59.839 --> 00:04:04.240
So if you say yes to that, we're going to clap twice, OK?

00:04:04.759 --> 00:04:08.119
OK, so that's a couple of people.

00:04:08.119 --> 00:04:09.800
Good analog survey approach.

00:04:09.800 --> 00:04:18.440
OK, so how many people after having that experience left that topic for a while?

00:04:18.440 --> 00:04:23.079
So we have no idea how many people that is, but at least it's a few, right?

00:04:23.079 --> 00:04:29.480
So feeling like you belong in that course is really important for how you continue to

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:32.399
learn that topic.

00:04:32.399 --> 00:04:35.880
So in the carpentries, I'll talk about how many workshops we've taught, but it's been

00:04:35.880 --> 00:04:37.440
a lot.

00:04:37.440 --> 00:04:42.040
And so something that we realized when we were trying to measure our impact or think

00:04:42.040 --> 00:04:46.720
about what was important is that we realized it's not about a specific skill set.

00:04:46.720 --> 00:04:49.679
It's not about, can you parse this line of code?

00:04:49.679 --> 00:04:52.679
Can you construct a function in this way?

00:04:52.679 --> 00:04:57.559
But that it's about establishing a growth mindset around data and code and people feeling

00:04:57.559 --> 00:05:01.959
like they belong, that data science is for them.

00:05:01.959 --> 00:05:06.160
And so the growth mindset is a bit of a loaded term right now, and does it work?

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:07.760
Does it not work?

00:05:07.760 --> 00:05:12.440
So I'm not going to talk about that, but what I do want to say is, what does it mean to

00:05:12.440 --> 00:05:15.480
us right now when we say that?

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:22.519
So it means confidence, the confidence that this is something you can do or continue doing,

00:05:22.519 --> 00:05:27.720
that we focus on effort and incremental learning and not outcomes, that you don't need to immediately

00:05:27.720 --> 00:05:29.519
get something right.

00:05:29.519 --> 00:05:34.959
And seeing mistakes as opportunities for learning and having an opportunity for a safe space

00:05:34.959 --> 00:05:40.079
to make those mistakes to continue learning.

00:05:40.079 --> 00:05:44.559
So we want to work towards this growth mindset using inclusive pedagogy.

00:05:44.559 --> 00:05:50.040
So not focusing, we do focus on what we teach, that is a big thing, and I'm not talking about

00:05:50.040 --> 00:05:54.000
that right now, but how we teach.

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:56.200
And so that's what I'm going to talk about now.

00:05:56.200 --> 00:05:59.760
And so we're thinking about it in the context, and for the people that are in the room that

00:05:59.760 --> 00:06:03.399
are saying, I've never actually heard us say it this way, that is true.

00:06:03.399 --> 00:06:07.880
So we're thinking about taking all of the things that we do every day and stepping back

00:06:07.880 --> 00:06:10.959
and saying, what is it that this represents?

00:06:10.959 --> 00:06:18.920
It's these four A's, accessible, approachable, aligned, and active.

00:06:18.920 --> 00:06:22.880
So what do these things mean in the context of a learning environment?

00:06:22.880 --> 00:06:23.940
Accessible.

00:06:23.940 --> 00:06:28.019
So available in a time and a place where people can attend.

00:06:28.019 --> 00:06:34.299
So that's really important, right, because if you have things on weekends and you can't

00:06:34.299 --> 00:06:37.779
have childcare on weekends, you can't go on weekends, but maybe you can't get away from

00:06:37.779 --> 00:06:43.299
work during the week, or maybe you only can do evenings, maybe you only can do online

00:06:43.299 --> 00:06:45.100
because you can't leave your house.

00:06:45.100 --> 00:06:49.940
There are a lot of different ways that we can deliver things so that it's accessible

00:06:49.940 --> 00:06:54.339
to people in a time and a place that works for them.

00:06:54.339 --> 00:06:59.820
That it's welcoming, so that when they are there, that it is accessible to them because

00:06:59.820 --> 00:07:01.779
of the environment that's created.

00:07:01.779 --> 00:07:06.660
So in all of our workshops, we have a code of conduct, and we have a reporting structure.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:10.899
Those are both important, not just having a code of conduct.

00:07:10.899 --> 00:07:14.579
And we start with that, I appreciate in this meeting, right, that they started with a code

00:07:14.579 --> 00:07:19.739
of conduct, because it sets the stage as saying that this is a place that is supposed to be

00:07:19.739 --> 00:07:24.100
accessible and welcoming to everybody.

00:07:24.100 --> 00:07:27.980
And being proactive about ensuring accessibility needs.

00:07:27.980 --> 00:07:34.140
So I think we still have work to do in this front, but looking at your website resources,

00:07:34.140 --> 00:07:38.540
looking at your color schemes, a lot of great R packages around that.

00:07:38.540 --> 00:07:44.739
Looking at, through the lens of accessibility, for everybody, not just for the largest percentage

00:07:44.739 --> 00:07:47.739
of learners.

00:07:48.739 --> 00:07:49.739
Approachable.

00:07:49.739 --> 00:07:55.339
So, great, this is accessible, I can go to this thing, but do I want to go?

00:07:55.339 --> 00:07:56.899
Is this for me?

00:07:56.899 --> 00:08:01.140
And so that starts at the very beginning, in advertising and recruitment for the workshop.

00:08:01.140 --> 00:08:07.980
If this is for beginners, say this is for people with little to no prior experience.

00:08:07.980 --> 00:08:13.500
In this domain, map out, essentially, what your persona is of this person who can come,

00:08:13.500 --> 00:08:17.700
and tell these people who it's for and why they're welcome.

00:08:17.700 --> 00:08:20.980
Invite them to participate.

00:08:20.980 --> 00:08:23.420
Meeting learners where they are.

00:08:23.420 --> 00:08:30.100
So understanding that someone might be working in Excel, and that they maybe have, you know,

00:08:30.100 --> 00:08:33.780
primarily only had experience with their computers for Netflix.

00:08:33.780 --> 00:08:36.539
That's not a bad thing, that's where people are.

00:08:36.539 --> 00:08:40.500
Let's appreciate where people are and meet them there, rather than hoping that they're

00:08:40.500 --> 00:08:42.299
someplace else.

00:08:42.299 --> 00:08:44.340
And that is what helps make it approachable.

00:08:44.340 --> 00:08:48.299
We're creating that on-ramp for them, we're putting the on-ramp in front of them, instead

00:08:48.299 --> 00:08:52.900
of way the heck over there, or a humongous step in front of them to start.

00:08:52.900 --> 00:08:58.299
And that helps overcome the activation barriers to getting started.

00:08:58.299 --> 00:09:00.979
And then, of course, the mistakes are the pedagogy.

00:09:00.979 --> 00:09:08.099
So in our workshops, we'll talk about how we use a participatory live coding approach.

00:09:08.099 --> 00:09:12.559
So you always make mistakes when you're doing it in person, but we treat that as a part

00:09:12.559 --> 00:09:14.159
of the learning opportunity.

00:09:14.159 --> 00:09:19.280
Seeing other people, when they make mistakes, when they don't know what's going on, helps

00:09:19.280 --> 00:09:24.479
you understand, one, how you approach fixing a mistake, and also that that's okay.

00:09:24.479 --> 00:09:28.320
And I think, since we're supposed to quote Hadley, that's something that Hadley always

00:09:28.320 --> 00:09:32.479
says, is, right, that, you know, he has to Google things, right?

00:09:32.479 --> 00:09:36.880
It's not that everyone knows everything and never makes mistakes.

00:09:36.880 --> 00:09:40.200
Aligned.

00:09:40.200 --> 00:09:45.520
So they're all sort of similar, but the aligned is really about the motivation.

00:09:45.520 --> 00:09:48.640
So teaching with datasets that are relevant to the user.

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:54.320
So we had a great discussion this morning at the Data for Good BoF about using datasets

00:09:54.320 --> 00:09:59.760
that the students were really excited about, and that got them excited about the topic.

00:09:59.760 --> 00:10:04.239
Because if you're trying to introduce some topic that they're not excited about and teach

00:10:04.239 --> 00:10:07.400
the skills on top of that, you're trying to do two things at the same time.

00:10:07.400 --> 00:10:11.159
So starting with a topic that people are excited about.

00:10:11.159 --> 00:10:14.760
Teaching the skills and perspectives relevant to their current work.

00:10:14.760 --> 00:10:18.679
So yeah, you might hope that, you know, down the road, think that everybody should know

00:10:18.679 --> 00:10:24.039
C++, but if that person is not going to use it right away in their context, then it's

00:10:24.039 --> 00:10:29.359
not going to be something that sticks, that understands, they understand why it's important,

00:10:29.359 --> 00:10:33.559
and will motivate them to keep using the tool.

00:10:33.559 --> 00:10:34.799
Instructors that are current in the field.

00:10:34.799 --> 00:10:36.820
So peer instruction.

00:10:36.820 --> 00:10:41.900
So some of our best instructors are people who were learners only a year ago.

00:10:41.900 --> 00:10:46.099
Because when they understand the misconceptions, they're very familiar with what that process

00:10:46.099 --> 00:10:47.099
looks like.

00:10:47.099 --> 00:10:52.739
So when they see that someone doesn't understand something, then they can relate to that, help

00:10:52.739 --> 00:10:54.719
guide someone through that process.

00:10:54.719 --> 00:10:56.020
They also are peers.

00:10:56.020 --> 00:11:00.260
They're an ecologist or a social scientist or an economist.

00:11:00.260 --> 00:11:02.820
And so they can put the things into context.

00:11:02.820 --> 00:11:05.659
And so it helps in guiding their learning as well.

00:11:05.659 --> 00:11:06.979
And teaching the current tools.

00:11:06.979 --> 00:11:09.559
So looking around, what is it that people are using?

00:11:09.559 --> 00:11:11.940
Teach what you're using in your work.

00:11:11.940 --> 00:11:17.059
And again, that's going to be something that helps them continue with their learning.

00:11:17.059 --> 00:11:18.580
And finally, active.

00:11:18.580 --> 00:11:21.940
And this is one of the ones that we really like to talk about.

00:11:21.940 --> 00:11:28.179
And this is a little bit that idea of guided practice, that you can get feedback on what

00:11:28.179 --> 00:11:29.859
you're doing as you're learning.

00:11:29.859 --> 00:11:33.979
That's one of the challenges of learning on your own, is that you often can't get that

00:11:34.020 --> 00:11:36.460
feedback right away.

00:11:36.460 --> 00:11:41.539
And so participatory live coding, that's the instructor at the front of the room going

00:11:41.539 --> 00:11:46.340
through code and having the learners go through it at the same time.

00:11:46.340 --> 00:11:50.219
So you're participating together in doing that coding.

00:11:50.219 --> 00:11:52.419
An I, we, you model for teaching.

00:11:52.419 --> 00:11:57.140
So I describe something, we do it together, you do it yourself.

00:11:57.140 --> 00:12:03.340
It gives you a chance to try it out on your own, but not completely without a safety net.

00:12:03.340 --> 00:12:08.299
All of our curriculum is open source and collaboratively developed and updated to represent

00:12:08.299 --> 00:12:09.460
the current practices.

00:12:09.460 --> 00:12:12.460
So our curriculum is active, actually, in and of itself.

00:12:12.460 --> 00:12:18.780
Oh, I see, I, Kara Wu, in fact, introduced Tidyverse to our data carpentry lessons.

00:12:18.780 --> 00:12:23.659
So we have people who are in the field that are active and engaged in the topics so that

00:12:23.659 --> 00:12:27.020
they kind of meet those first three A's.

00:12:27.020 --> 00:12:31.099
We have helpers in our workshops, so not only the instructor at the front of the room, but

00:12:31.099 --> 00:12:37.179
someone who goes around and talks with people to create a strong five to one student ratio.

00:12:37.179 --> 00:12:42.700
And then finally, our most famous probably is formative assessment through using sticky

00:12:42.700 --> 00:12:44.099
notes.

00:12:44.099 --> 00:12:49.500
So if you completed an exercise, you put a green sticky note on your laptop, and if you're

00:12:49.500 --> 00:12:54.219
having trouble, you put a pink sticky note, and someone will come help you.

00:12:54.219 --> 00:12:57.700
So it's a way during the workshop, not just waiting until the end and saying, oh, my gosh,

00:12:57.700 --> 00:12:58.700
did people get it?

00:12:59.299 --> 00:13:03.979
of seeing as you go, getting a sense of the room, assigning help when it's needed.

00:13:03.979 --> 00:13:11.219
So it's a formative assessment, assessing as you're going during the workshop.

00:13:11.219 --> 00:13:15.900
So that was a bunch, like our whole concepts of instructor training.

00:13:15.900 --> 00:13:19.780
That is two days smushed into about five minutes.

00:13:19.780 --> 00:13:23.299
So you saw some of the instructor training earlier this week if you were there.

00:13:23.700 --> 00:13:27.820
But all of our instructor training curriculum is also online.

00:13:27.820 --> 00:13:30.940
Like all of our lessons, it's all CC by.

00:13:30.940 --> 00:13:39.179
So the question is, if what we're aiming for is confidence and continued learning, how

00:13:39.179 --> 00:13:40.659
are we doing?

00:13:40.659 --> 00:13:46.500
How does this approach work in terms of meeting those identified goals?

00:13:46.500 --> 00:13:48.140
So first, how many workshops have we taught?

00:13:48.140 --> 00:13:54.780
So since 2012, we have over 1,600 instructors, over 39,000 learners, and we've taught over

00:13:54.780 --> 00:14:00.140
1,700 workshops.

00:14:00.140 --> 00:14:04.739
So not only have we taught a lot of them, we've had a global reach.

00:14:04.739 --> 00:14:09.900
So this is a map of the workshops over time, getting brighter in color as we have more

00:14:09.900 --> 00:14:10.900
workshops.

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:14.619
And Francois did this great plot, and I'm super excited about it.

00:14:15.099 --> 00:14:18.500
And you can see we got Antarctica in the last year.

00:14:18.500 --> 00:14:21.179
So very excited about that.

00:14:21.179 --> 00:14:22.179
One person taught that.

00:14:22.179 --> 00:14:24.780
We think we should just put her name on Antarctica.

00:14:24.780 --> 00:14:27.179
She just claims the whole thing.

00:14:27.179 --> 00:14:32.619
So we've also been able to have, because of this volunteer approach, approaching teaching

00:14:32.619 --> 00:14:38.179
from the perspective of meeting learners where they are and scaling impact, we've been able

00:14:38.179 --> 00:14:40.940
to reach a lot of different communities.

00:14:41.940 --> 00:14:44.380
Okay.

00:14:44.380 --> 00:14:46.820
So the first one we're trying to achieve is confidence.

00:14:46.820 --> 00:14:48.260
So how do we do?

00:14:48.260 --> 00:14:50.219
So this is a survey of students.

00:14:50.219 --> 00:14:52.059
This is just data carpentry.

00:14:52.059 --> 00:14:57.500
It's not all R. Most of data carpentries are R, but some are Python as well.

00:14:57.500 --> 00:15:00.500
So pre and post, two days.

00:15:00.500 --> 00:15:06.820
How much has people's perception of their abilities and their confidence changed?

00:15:06.820 --> 00:15:12.460
So the first question is I'm able to write a program that would solve small problems.

00:15:12.460 --> 00:15:16.539
So we see these full point differences around write programs.

00:15:16.539 --> 00:15:18.859
I'm able to search for answers.

00:15:18.859 --> 00:15:24.820
I'm able to make my programming more reproducible, overcome a problem, become more efficient

00:15:24.820 --> 00:15:25.820
in programming.

00:15:25.820 --> 00:15:31.340
I know to keep my raw data raw, I'm very invested in that question.

00:15:31.340 --> 00:15:33.520
And then that last one, confidence in programming.

00:15:33.520 --> 00:15:36.700
So I have confidence in my ability to program.

00:15:36.700 --> 00:15:40.619
That was one of our lowest scores right before the workshop, and it's increasing a full point

00:15:40.619 --> 00:15:42.900
in two days.

00:15:42.900 --> 00:15:47.500
You might say maybe that confidence is misplaced after two days.

00:15:47.500 --> 00:15:50.739
But the point is that they feel like it's for them.

00:15:50.739 --> 00:15:53.500
People feel like it's for them, right?

00:15:53.500 --> 00:15:57.219
And these are some of the words that people use to describe the workshop that reflect

00:15:57.219 --> 00:16:02.780
those ideals that we have around inclusivity and accessibility.

00:16:02.780 --> 00:16:06.380
And you always see instructors and helpful.

00:16:06.380 --> 00:16:11.780
So it represents kind of a lot of those things that I've talked about with our practices.

00:16:11.780 --> 00:16:16.840
Not only are people more confident after two days, but when we survey people more than

00:16:16.840 --> 00:16:21.739
six months after a workshop, and this does have a bias because only certain people answer

00:16:21.739 --> 00:16:28.099
surveys that you send out way long later, what is the percentage?

00:16:28.099 --> 00:16:33.099
Basically almost 100% of people more than six months after a workshop say that they

00:16:33.099 --> 00:16:36.099
are more confident.

00:16:36.099 --> 00:16:37.099
I don't know.

00:16:37.099 --> 00:16:38.099
You don't look surprised.

00:16:38.099 --> 00:16:39.099
I'm surprised.

00:16:39.099 --> 00:16:40.099
I do programming.

00:16:40.099 --> 00:16:44.940
I don't always feel more confident after I've spent a day programming, I can tell you.

00:16:44.940 --> 00:16:50.539
So this to me is not only this sort of short-term effect of two days, but the long-term this

00:16:50.539 --> 00:16:54.780
feeling persists is very important.

00:16:54.780 --> 00:16:55.780
Continued learning.

00:16:55.780 --> 00:16:57.979
Do people go on to continue learning?

00:16:57.979 --> 00:17:01.059
So this is, again, that longer-term survey.

00:17:01.059 --> 00:17:04.219
Have you gone on to continue learning after the workshop?

00:17:04.219 --> 00:17:09.540
So most people agree or strongly agree that they've gone on to continue learning.

00:17:09.540 --> 00:17:12.500
And these are using these skills in their work.

00:17:12.500 --> 00:17:15.699
Improving overall efficiency, managing data.

00:17:15.699 --> 00:17:18.660
So people are regularly using these practices.

00:17:18.660 --> 00:17:23.180
Again, when they come back to reflect on what this has meant to them, what they're capable

00:17:23.180 --> 00:17:27.819
of now, these are some of the words that they use.

00:17:27.819 --> 00:17:30.819
And they strongly recommend their workshops to others.

00:17:30.819 --> 00:17:36.099
So almost 80% have recommended the workshop to someone else.

00:17:36.099 --> 00:17:40.020
Our net promoter score, if you're into net promoter scores, is like over nine.

00:17:40.020 --> 00:17:42.500
Is that the right thing?

00:17:42.500 --> 00:17:46.859
The number of people that want to recommend these to other people also reflects on how

00:17:46.859 --> 00:17:54.099
they felt about that experience, not just about what they thought they learned.

00:17:54.099 --> 00:17:55.819
So safe spaces for continued learning.

00:17:55.819 --> 00:17:59.900
That was that last one around a goat's mindset, because we want people to continue learning.

00:17:59.979 --> 00:18:01.619
How do they do that?

00:18:01.619 --> 00:18:05.900
So one way that they're seeing that, people continue to engage with our community, sometimes

00:18:05.900 --> 00:18:10.900
going on to become instructors or helpers.

00:18:10.900 --> 00:18:12.579
But they do a lot of other things.

00:18:12.579 --> 00:18:15.979
Sometimes they use carpentry lessons, they use short courses, they go to meetups, they

00:18:15.979 --> 00:18:18.699
go to semester-long courses.

00:18:18.699 --> 00:18:21.660
So when we talk about this after the workshop, we do some of that.

00:18:21.660 --> 00:18:25.020
But what they're really doing is they're diving into a community of practice.

00:18:25.020 --> 00:18:28.780
And so seeing these practices that exist is really important.

00:18:28.780 --> 00:18:33.540
And so we're lucky here with Our Ladies and all the things that people talked about, that

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:36.780
they do have welcoming communities of practice to continue to learn in.

00:18:36.780 --> 00:18:43.699
So these are some elements that make this important.

00:18:43.699 --> 00:18:47.260
And so then the question is, so great, awesome.

00:18:47.260 --> 00:18:48.260
People like it.

00:18:48.260 --> 00:18:51.500
But I said at the beginning that one of our goals is reaching diverse communities.

00:18:51.500 --> 00:18:52.819
And how are we doing?

00:18:52.819 --> 00:18:55.660
Well, gender, I guess, would say pretty rapid.

00:18:55.660 --> 00:18:59.380
This is just in the United States, because that's the only place we collect demographic

00:18:59.380 --> 00:19:02.319
data because of legal reasons.

00:19:02.319 --> 00:19:04.699
We're not doing so well.

00:19:04.699 --> 00:19:07.239
So we need to do better.

00:19:07.239 --> 00:19:11.660
So there are elements of creating a space where people feel welcome.

00:19:11.660 --> 00:19:13.099
There's more opportunities for that.

00:19:13.099 --> 00:19:16.260
There's more opportunities for recruitment.

00:19:16.260 --> 00:19:21.619
And so what we want to say here is that with this ecosystem, with this community of practice

00:19:21.619 --> 00:19:24.939
that people are building, with all of these different teaching practices that we together

00:19:25.219 --> 00:19:26.859
are an ecosystem.

00:19:26.859 --> 00:19:30.579
And that if we want to go fast, we can go alone.

00:19:30.579 --> 00:19:32.420
And then if we want to go far, we go together.

00:19:32.420 --> 00:19:35.099
And there's great opportunities for that here.

00:19:35.099 --> 00:19:40.459
And we look forward to continuing to work with all of these communities and building

00:19:40.459 --> 00:19:42.979
our future together around data.

00:19:42.979 --> 00:19:43.219
Thank you.

